Emergency Response Program
The release prevention program incorporates the Riverside facility¿s comprehensive emergency response plan.  The emergency response program places special emphasis on handling accidental releases of aqueous ammonia and coordination of emergency response with local fire departments and other emergency response organizations such as the Rock County LEPC.  The response plan details the emergency response structure and includes personnel responsibilities and procedures within that structure.  In addition, the plan includes procedures for notification of local agencies in the event of an incident, facility evacuation, and decontamination.  Finally, the plan discusses emergency preparedness and planning, including plans for conducting emergency response team training and drills.

Calpine¿s management is committed to supporting the emergency response (ER) organization and its prescribed functions.  ER team members are drawn from the existing employee pool and the organizational concept fosters pride and empha

sizes concerns for safe operation of the Riverside facility.  The well-defined ER organization operates in conjunction with the local Fire Department and the Rock County LEPC to alleviate safety concerns about handling aqueous ammonia. 
Auditing Program
Riverside Energy has developed an auditing program for the Riverside facility¿s ammonia system.  This audit program includes elements from the Program 3 requirements and has been established to provide a mechanism for periodic reviews of the various aspects of the RMP including:
-	the physical ammonia system;
-	hazard review;
-	operation of the system;
-	maintenance procedures;
-	training procedures; and
-	incident investigation procedures.

Although not specifically required by the RMP regulations for Program 2 facilities, audits are conducted every three years.  A copy of the audit form used to conduct these audits is included in this document.

Incident Investigation Program
Riverside Energy has developed an incident investigation program for the Riverside facility¿s ammonia system.  This program includes elements from the Program 3 requirements and has been established to provide a mechanism for determining root causes of accidental releases of ammonia and preventing such events in the future.   A copy of the form used to conduct incident investigation is included in this document.
